{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module-to-client handoff: request builder + API client wiring. A unit test of a helper could miss dropped fields during assembly, but no real OS/network/model output is required. Higher levels were rejected because behavior text is only about request content (\"includes the complete list\"), not live provider behavior.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module to a stub API client that captures outbound payloads; invoke classification with a known taxonomy and assert every outbound request contains the full label list, in the expected field.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is response-handling across module boundary (API response -> normalization/validation -> public return). A pure unit test of normalization alone can miss miswiring from transport layer fields. Higher levels were rejected because behavior text specifies deterministic mapping of an invalid label, not real network or model-quality dependence.","test_description":"Use a stub API client that returns an out-of-taxonomy label (e.g., \"medical\"); call classify() and assert returned value is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior is explicitly one local transformation (normalization determinism) with fixed input/output and no I/O boundary. Integration+ would be unnecessary because failure is in pure logic, not inter-module handoff.","test_description":"Call normalization with the same raw response object/string multiple times and assert identical final label each time (table-driven over representative casing/whitespace variants).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Requires repeated real AI API calls and checks consistency against provider-output variability. Mocks hide non-determinism and provider behavior drift. Workflow was rejected because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-stage agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N live classifications for identical document+taxonomy against the real provider, record raw provider responses and final labels, and assert label changes only occur when raw provider output changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at handoff between budget policy/token counter and dispatch path (whether request is truncated/rejected before send). A unit test of budget math alone may miss an actual send occurring. Higher levels were rejected because behavior text is pre-dispatch enforcement, not live provider/network behavior.","test_description":"Configure a low token budget, pass an over-budget document, and use a stub client to verify either (a) request is truncated per policy and then sent within limit, or (b) request is rejected and no dispatch occurs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior depends on real provider-reported usage from an AI API call; a mock can always report compliant usage and hide real tokenizer/provider accounting mismatches. System was considered, but rejected because behavior explicitly targets AI provider semantics (\"Provider-reported token usage\"), which requires the real model service path.","test_description":"Execute live calls with representative documents and taxonomy, collect provider usage metadata from responses, and assert reported total tokens are <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure is retry orchestration (error interpretation, backoff, second attempt) across module + client interaction. This can be reproduced with a deterministic stub returning rate-limit then success. Higher levels were rejected because behavior text is transport/control-flow handling, not model output quality or multi-agent sequencing.","test_description":"Stub API returns rate-limit error on first call and success on second; verify classifier waits/backs off (using fake clock or measured delay policy) and eventually returns successful label instead of surfacing the initial error